				\begin{document}$${\text{Ti}}\left( {{\text{OBu}}^{{\text{n}}} } \right)_{{4}} + {\text{ acacH}}\rightarrow {\text{Ti}}\left( {{\text{OBu}}^{{\text{n}}} } \right)_{{{4} - {\text{x}}}} + {\text{ xBuOH}}$$\end{document}As such, the standard hydrolysis and condensation reactions participating in the conventional sol–gel process can be controlled through the hydrolysis and complexation molar ratios. We define these two ratios as rc = [acac]/[Ti] and rw = [H2O]/[Ti], respectively. These ratios can be varied in order to obtain precipitates, opaque gels, transparent gels, stable sols and cluster solutions58. To obtain transparent gels, the values we use for the hydrolysis and complexation ratios are summarized in the Table 1.Table 1
